</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">As survival rates continue to increase for patients with childhood and adult malignancies, imaging utilization in these patients will likely increase substantially. It is important to detect disease recurrence and to recognize the potential complications that occur after treatment with oncologic medications and therapeutic radiation. The most common cardiotoxic side effect of the anthracycline drug class is a dose-dependent decline in ejection fraction, which may result in dilated cardiomyopathy. Multiple-uptake gated acquisition (MUGA) scanning plays an important role in diagnosis of this subclinical cardiac dysfunction. Other less common cardiotoxic side effects of chemotherapeutic medications include arrhythmia, myocarditis, coronary artery disease, tamponade, pericarditis, and pericardial effusion. Radiation therapy can also lead to cardiotoxicity when the heart or pericardium is included in the radiation portal. Radiation-induced conditions include pericardial disease, coronary artery disease, valvular disease, and cardiomyopathy. Many of these side effects are asymptomatic until late in the course of the disease. With imaging, these pathologic conditions can often be diagnosed before symptom onset, which may allow early intervention. Radiologists should be familiar with the current knowledge and pathophysiology regarding cardiac complications related to chemotherapy and radiation therapy of malignant neoplasms and the appearances of treatment-related cardiotoxicity that can be found at radiography, nuclear medicine examinations, and cross-sectional imaging. Supplemental material available at <i><a href="http://radiographics.rsna.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1148/rg.336125005/-/DC1">http://radiographics.rsna.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1148/rg.336125005/-/DC1</a></i>.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2013</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.336125005">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.336125005">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig01.jpeg" height="869" width="1244" aria-labelledby="fig01" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Diagram illustrates the free radical chain reaction. Anthracyclines produce free radicals that set off a chain reaction, leading to cell membrane erosion and eventual cell apoptosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig01">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig02a.jpeg" height="644" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig02a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Adriamycin-induced dilated cardiomyopathy after treatment of metastatic breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows cardiomegaly and an implantable cardioverter-defibrillator with electrodes in the superior vena cava and right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Coronal computed tomographic (CT) image shows marked dilatation of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. At echocardiography (not shown), the left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) was 17%. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows dilatation of both the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. The electrode (arrow) is incompletely visualized.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig02a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig02b.jpeg" height="588" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig02b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Adriamycin-induced dilated cardiomyopathy after treatment of metastatic breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows cardiomegaly and an implantable cardioverter-defibrillator with electrodes in the superior vena cava and right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Coronal computed tomographic (CT) image shows marked dilatation of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. At echocardiography (not shown), the left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) was 17%. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows dilatation of both the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. The electrode (arrow) is incompletely visualized.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig02b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig02c.jpeg" height="588" width="925" aria-labelledby="fig02c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> Adriamycin-induced dilated cardiomyopathy after treatment of metastatic breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows cardiomegaly and an implantable cardioverter-defibrillator with electrodes in the superior vena cava and right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Coronal computed tomographic (CT) image shows marked dilatation of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. At echocardiography (not shown), the left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) was 17%. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows dilatation of both the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> and left ventricle <i>(LV)</i>. The electrode (arrow) is incompletely visualized.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig02c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig03.jpeg" height="1468" width="1250" aria-labelledby="fig03" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Acute myeloid leukemia with anthracycline- and cytarabine-induced cardiomyopathy. Pretherapy evaluation showed a normal ejection fraction (not shown). After therapy, single photon emission CT was performed with technetium-99m–labeled tetrofosmin. Myocardial perfusion images obtained in the short axis (top four rows) and vertical long axis (bottom two rows) at rest and stress show a reduced ejection fraction of 40%, global hypokinesis, and a reversible apical anterior wall defect (arrows) indicating ischemia. Coronary CT image (not shown) showed no coronary atherosclerosis. The cause of the reversible defect on perfusion images was unclear and could be secondary to coronary artery disease not seen at CT angiography or possibly an imaging artifact.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig03">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig04a.jpeg" height="1512" width="731" aria-labelledby="fig04a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Doxorubicin-induced cardiomyopathy (see also <a href="http://radiographics.rsna.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1148/rg.336125005/-/DC1">Movies 1</a> and <a href="http://radiographics.rsna.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1148/rg.336125005/-/DC1">2</a>). <i>Bkgnd</i> = background subtraction area used for calculating ejection fraction. <b>(a)</b> Pretherapy MUGA scans obtained in the left anterior oblique <i>(LAO)</i> projection at end-diastole (top) and end-systole (bottom) show a normal to slightly elevated ejection fraction of 74% (areas outlined with colored lines delineate left ventricular cavity). <b>(b)</b> Posttherapy MUGA scans obtained 2 years later at end-diastole (top) and end-systole (bottom) show a markedly decreased ejection fraction of 24% (areas outlined with colored lines delineate left ventricular cavity).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig04a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig04b.jpeg" height="1511" width="723" aria-labelledby="fig04b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Doxorubicin-induced cardiomyopathy (see also <a href="http://radiographics.rsna.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1148/rg.336125005/-/DC1">Movies 1</a> and <a href="http://radiographics.rsna.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1148/rg.336125005/-/DC1">2</a>). <i>Bkgnd</i> = background subtraction area used for calculating ejection fraction. <b>(a)</b> Pretherapy MUGA scans obtained in the left anterior oblique <i>(LAO)</i> projection at end-diastole (top) and end-systole (bottom) show a normal to slightly elevated ejection fraction of 74% (areas outlined with colored lines delineate left ventricular cavity). <b>(b)</b> Posttherapy MUGA scans obtained 2 years later at end-diastole (top) and end-systole (bottom) show a markedly decreased ejection fraction of 24% (areas outlined with colored lines delineate left ventricular cavity).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig04b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig05.jpeg" height="1508" width="1350" aria-labelledby="fig05" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> Modified Simpson method of calculating LVEF with MR imaging from three selected short-axis steady-state free precession images obtained at end-diastole (left column) and end-systole (right column). A region of interest (green circle) is drawn around the left ventricular cavity at end-diastole and end-systole for each anatomic level. The total volume at end-diastole and end-systole (all axial images summed) is multiplied by the section thickness and intersection gap to obtain the EDV and ESV, respectively. LVEF = (EDV - ESV)/EDV. The LVEF in this case was normal at 56%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig05">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig06a.jpeg" height="657" width="933" aria-labelledby="fig06a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Bexarotene-related (Targretin, from the retinoid class of drugs) pericarditis following treatment of mycosis fungoides. CT images (<b>b</b> obtained at a slightly higher level than <b>a</b>) show a small pericardial effusion with thin, faint pericardial enhancement (arrow) and moderate to large bilateral pleural effusions. CT images (not shown) obtained after corticosteroid therapy showed nearly complete resolution of the effusion and pericardial thickening. The cause of pericarditis was attributed to the chemotherapeutic drug after elimination of other causes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig06a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig06b.jpeg" height="657" width="942" aria-labelledby="fig06b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Bexarotene-related (Targretin, from the retinoid class of drugs) pericarditis following treatment of mycosis fungoides. CT images (<b>b</b> obtained at a slightly higher level than <b>a</b>) show a small pericardial effusion with thin, faint pericardial enhancement (arrow) and moderate to large bilateral pleural effusions. CT images (not shown) obtained after corticosteroid therapy showed nearly complete resolution of the effusion and pericardial thickening. The cause of pericarditis was attributed to the chemotherapeutic drug after elimination of other causes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig06b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig07a.jpeg" height="762" width="867" aria-labelledby="fig07a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Anthracycline- and radiation therapy–related pericardial effusion. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph obtained 2 months before presentation shows mild cardiomegaly. <b>(b)</b> Posttherapy MUGA scan obtained at the time of presentation shows a normal ejection fraction but a large photopenic defect (arrows) surrounding the heart. <b>(c)</b> Chest radiograph obtained after the MUGA scanning shows interval-apparent cardiac enlargement. <b>(d)</b> Coronal CT image reveals a large pericardial effusion (*). The effusion was thought to be secondary to anthracycline and radiation therapy after lymphoma was excluded.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig07a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig07b.jpeg" height="733" width="766" aria-labelledby="fig07b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Anthracycline- and radiation therapy–related pericardial effusion. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph obtained 2 months before presentation shows mild cardiomegaly. <b>(b)</b> Posttherapy MUGA scan obtained at the time of presentation shows a normal ejection fraction but a large photopenic defect (arrows) surrounding the heart. <b>(c)</b> Chest radiograph obtained after the MUGA scanning shows interval-apparent cardiac enlargement. <b>(d)</b> Coronal CT image reveals a large pericardial effusion (*). The effusion was thought to be secondary to anthracycline and radiation therapy after lymphoma was excluded.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig07b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig07c.jpeg" height="762" width="808" aria-labelledby="fig07c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Anthracycline- and radiation therapy–related pericardial effusion. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph obtained 2 months before presentation shows mild cardiomegaly. <b>(b)</b> Posttherapy MUGA scan obtained at the time of presentation shows a normal ejection fraction but a large photopenic defect (arrows) surrounding the heart. <b>(c)</b> Chest radiograph obtained after the MUGA scanning shows interval-apparent cardiac enlargement. <b>(d)</b> Coronal CT image reveals a large pericardial effusion (*). The effusion was thought to be secondary to anthracycline and radiation therapy after lymphoma was excluded.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig07c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig07d.jpeg" height="733" width="909" aria-labelledby="fig07d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span> Anthracycline- and radiation therapy–related pericardial effusion. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph obtained 2 months before presentation shows mild cardiomegaly. <b>(b)</b> Posttherapy MUGA scan obtained at the time of presentation shows a normal ejection fraction but a large photopenic defect (arrows) surrounding the heart. <b>(c)</b> Chest radiograph obtained after the MUGA scanning shows interval-apparent cardiac enlargement. <b>(d)</b> Coronal CT image reveals a large pericardial effusion (*). The effusion was thought to be secondary to anthracycline and radiation therapy after lymphoma was excluded.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig07d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig08.jpeg" height="793" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig08" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Pericarditis after radiation therapy for esophageal cancer. Axial CT image shows a pericardial effusion with a mildly enhancing pericardium (arrows), a finding indicative of inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig08">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig09a.jpeg" height="822" width="695" aria-labelledby="fig09a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Asymptomatic chemoradiation-induced pericardial effusion. Axial steady-state free precession MR image <b>(a)</b> and axial contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> obtained at separate times approximately 3 years after completion of chemoradiation for stage IIA endobronchial non–small cell lung cancer show a small to moderate pericardial effusion (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig09a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig09b.jpeg" height="822" width="630" aria-labelledby="fig09b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Asymptomatic chemoradiation-induced pericardial effusion. Axial steady-state free precession MR image <b>(a)</b> and axial contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> obtained at separate times approximately 3 years after completion of chemoradiation for stage IIA endobronchial non–small cell lung cancer show a small to moderate pericardial effusion (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig09b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig10.jpeg" height="706" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Calcific pericarditis following mantle radiation for Hodgkin lymphoma. Axial CT image shows anterior pericardial calcification (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig11a.jpeg" height="693" width="791" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Effusive-constrictive pericarditis following mantle radiation therapy for nodular mantle cell lymphoma. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> cine steady-state free precession MR images show extensive visceral (arrowhead) and parietal (arrow) pericardial thickening with a small pericardial effusion. Note the bilateral pleural effusions. <i>Ao</i> = aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig11b.jpeg" height="693" width="884" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Effusive-constrictive pericarditis following mantle radiation therapy for nodular mantle cell lymphoma. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> cine steady-state free precession MR images show extensive visceral (arrowhead) and parietal (arrow) pericardial thickening with a small pericardial effusion. Note the bilateral pleural effusions. <i>Ao</i> = aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig12a.jpeg" height="760" width="828" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Severe radiation-induced coronary artery disease that developed after whole-chest irradiation for Wilms tumor. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained at the level of the left main coronary artery shows extensive occlusive coronary atherosclerosis (arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained at a lower level shows sparing of the distal left anterior descending artery (arrow), typical of radiation-induced coronary artery disease. Note the patent saphenous vein graft lateral to the left anterior descending artery. <i>Ao</i> = aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig12b.jpeg" height="760" width="847" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Severe radiation-induced coronary artery disease that developed after whole-chest irradiation for Wilms tumor. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained at the level of the left main coronary artery shows extensive occlusive coronary atherosclerosis (arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained at a lower level shows sparing of the distal left anterior descending artery (arrow), typical of radiation-induced coronary artery disease. Note the patent saphenous vein graft lateral to the left anterior descending artery. <i>Ao</i> = aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig13a.jpeg" height="853" width="958" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Coronary artery disease in a 37-year-old man with no cardiovascular risk factors but with a history of receiving 39.6 Gy of mantle irradiation for Hodgkin lymphoma. Coronary artery disease was found at a screening examination. Axial <b>(a)</b> and curved multiplanar reformatted <b>(b)</b> images from coronary CT angiography show irregularity and approximately 40% narrowing (arrow, and inset in <b>a</b>) of the proximal left anterior descending artery by noncalcified plaque.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig13b.jpeg" height="853" width="717" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Coronary artery disease in a 37-year-old man with no cardiovascular risk factors but with a history of receiving 39.6 Gy of mantle irradiation for Hodgkin lymphoma. Coronary artery disease was found at a screening examination. Axial <b>(a)</b> and curved multiplanar reformatted <b>(b)</b> images from coronary CT angiography show irregularity and approximately 40% narrowing (arrow, and inset in <b>a</b>) of the proximal left anterior descending artery by noncalcified plaque.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig14a.jpeg" height="813" width="861" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Severe aortic stenosis secondary to mantle irradiation for Hodgkin lymphoma (see also <a href="http://radiographics.rsna.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1148/rg.336125005/-/DC1">Movie 3</a>). <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows aortic valve leaflet calcification (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Cine steady-state free precession image of the left ventricular outflow tract obtained during systole demonstrates a dephasing flow-void artifact (arrow) directed from the aortic valve into the ascending aorta, a finding indicative of aortic stenosis. <b>(c)</b> Cine steady-state free precession image obtained at the point of maximal aortic valve opening during systole shows a stenotic valve with thickened leaflets (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig14b.jpeg" height="813" width="814" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Severe aortic stenosis secondary to mantle irradiation for Hodgkin lymphoma (see also <a href="http://radiographics.rsna.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1148/rg.336125005/-/DC1">Movie 3</a>). <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows aortic valve leaflet calcification (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Cine steady-state free precession image of the left ventricular outflow tract obtained during systole demonstrates a dephasing flow-void artifact (arrow) directed from the aortic valve into the ascending aorta, a finding indicative of aortic stenosis. <b>(c)</b> Cine steady-state free precession image obtained at the point of maximal aortic valve opening during systole shows a stenotic valve with thickened leaflets (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig14c.jpeg" height="665" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span> Severe aortic stenosis secondary to mantle irradiation for Hodgkin lymphoma (see also <a href="http://radiographics.rsna.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1148/rg.336125005/-/DC1">Movie 3</a>). <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows aortic valve leaflet calcification (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Cine steady-state free precession image of the left ventricular outflow tract obtained during systole demonstrates a dephasing flow-void artifact (arrow) directed from the aortic valve into the ascending aorta, a finding indicative of aortic stenosis. <b>(c)</b> Cine steady-state free precession image obtained at the point of maximal aortic valve opening during systole shows a stenotic valve with thickened leaflets (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig15a.jpeg" height="908" width="890" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Severe aortic stenosis, porcelain aorta, and calcified pulmonary arterial wall secondary to chest radiation therapy for metastatic Wilms tumor. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows aortic valve leaflet calcification (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows a porcelain aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and calcification of the pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i> wall. Note the volume loss in the left upper lobe secondary to radiation fibrosis (arrow). The peak velocity across the valve at echocardiography (not shown) was 4.7 m/sec.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125005/asset/images/large/125005fig15b.jpeg" height="907" width="785" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Severe aortic stenosis, porcelain aorta, and calcified pulmonary arterial wall secondary to chest radiation therapy for metastatic Wilms tumor. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows aortic valve leaflet calcification (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image shows a porcelain aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and calcification of the pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i> wall. Note the volume loss in the left upper lobe secondary to radiation fibrosis (arrow). The peak velocity across the valve at echocardiography (not shown) was 4.7 m/sec.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125005&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Krischer JP, Epstein S, Cuthbertson DD, Goorin AM, Epstein ML, Lipshultz SE. Clinical cardiotoxicity following anthracycline treatment for childhood cancer: the Pediatric Oncology Group experience. <em>J Clin Oncol</em> 1997;15(4):1544–1552.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1200/JCO.1997.15.4.1544">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9193351/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Clinical+cardiotoxicity+following+anthracycline+treatment+for+childhood+cancer%3A+the+Pediatric+Oncology+Group+experience&amp;author=JP+Krischer&amp;author=S+Epstein&amp;author=DD+Cuthbertson&amp;author=AM+Goorin&amp;author=ML+Epstein&amp;author=SE+Lipshultz&amp;publication_year=1997&amp;journal=J+Clin+Oncol&amp;pages=1544-1552&amp;doi=10.1200%2FJCO.1997.15.4.1544&amp;pmid=9193351">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Simbre VC, Duffy SA, Dadlani GH, Miller TL, Lipshultz SE. Cardiotoxicity of cancer chemotherapy: implications for children. <em>Paediatr Drugs</em> 2005; 7(3):187–202.</div>